Enter Input : 
Enter Input : A few words about Dostoevsky himself may help the English reader to
Enter Input : understand his work.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : Dostoevsky was the son of a doctor. His parents were very hard-working
Enter Input : and deeply religious people, but so poor that they lived with their five
Enter Input : children in only two rooms. The father and mother spent their evenings
Enter Input : in reading aloud to their children, generally from books of a serious
Enter Input : character.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : Though always sickly and delicate Dostoevsky came out third in the
Enter Input : final examination of the Petersburg school of Engineering. There he had
Enter Input : already begun his first work, "Poor Folk."
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : This story was published by the poet Nekrassov in his review and
Enter Input : was received with acclamations. The shy, unknown youth found himself
Enter Input : instantly something of a celebrity. A brilliant and successful career
Enter Input : seemed to open before him, but those hopes were soon dashed. In 1849 he
Enter Input : was arrested.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : Though neither by temperament nor conviction a revolutionist, Dostoevsky
Enter Input : was one of a little group of young men who met together to read Fourier
Enter Input : and Proudhon. He was accused of "taking part in conversations against
Enter Input : the censorship, of reading a letter from Byelinsky to Gogol, and of
Enter Input : knowing of the intention to set up a printing press." Under Nicholas
Enter Input : I. (that "stern and just man," as Maurice Baring calls him) this was
Enter Input : enough, and he was condemned to death. After eight months' imprisonment
Enter Input : he was with twenty-one others taken out to the Semyonovsky Square to
Enter Input : be shot. Writing to his brother Mihail, Dostoevsky says: "They snapped
Enter Input : words over our heads, and they made us put on the white shirts worn by
Enter Input : persons condemned to death. Thereupon we were bound in threes to stakes,
Enter Input : to suffer execution. Being the third in the row, I concluded I had only
Enter Input : a few minutes of life before me. I thought of you and your dear ones and
Enter Input : I contrived to kiss Plestcheiev and Dourov, who were next to me, and to
Enter Input : bid them farewell. Suddenly the troops beat a tattoo, we were unbound,
Enter Input : brought back upon the scaffold, and informed that his Majesty had spared
Enter Input : us our lives." The sentence was commuted to hard labour.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : One of the prisoners, Grigoryev, went mad as soon as he was untied, and
Enter Input : never regained his sanity.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : The intense suffering of this experience left a lasting stamp on
Enter Input : Dostoevsky's mind. Though his religious temper led him in the end to
Enter Input : accept every suffering with resignation and to regard it as a blessing
Enter Input : in his own case, he constantly recurs to the subject in his writings.
Enter Input : He describes the awful agony of the condemned man and insists on the
Enter Input : cruelty of inflicting such torture. Then followed four years of penal
Enter Input : servitude, spent in the company of common criminals in Siberia, where
Enter Input : he began the "Dead House," and some years of service in a disciplinary
Enter Input : battalion.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : He had shown signs of some obscure nervous disease before his arrest
Enter Input : and this now developed into violent attacks of epilepsy, from which he
Enter Input : suffered for the rest of his life. The fits occurred three or four times
Enter Input : a year and were more frequent in periods of great strain. In 1859 he was
Enter Input : allowed to return to Russia. He started a journal--"Vremya," which was
Enter Input : forbidden by the Censorship through a misunderstanding. In 1864 he lost
Enter Input : his first wife and his brother Mihail. He was in terrible poverty, yet
Enter Input : he took upon himself the payment of his brother's debts. He started
Enter Input : another journal--"The Epoch," which within a few months was also
Enter Input : prohibited. He was weighed down by debt, his brother's family was
Enter Input : dependent on him, he was forced to write at heart-breaking speed, and is
Enter Input : said never to have corrected his work. The later years of his life were
Enter Input : much softened by the tenderness and devotion of his second wife.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : In June 1880 he made his famous speech at the unveiling of the
Enter Input : monument to Pushkin in Moscow and he was received with extraordinary
Enter Input : demonstrations of love and honour.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : A few months later Dostoevsky died. He was followed to the grave by a
Enter Input : vast multitude of mourners, who "gave the hapless man the funeral of a
Enter Input : king." He is still probably the most widely read writer in Russia.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : In the words of a Russian critic, who seeks to explain the feeling
