Enter Input : CHAPTER I
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : On an exceptionally hot evening early in July a young man came out of
Enter Input : the garret in which he lodged in S. Place and walked slowly, as though
Enter Input : in hesitation, towards K. bridge.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : He had successfully avoided meeting his landlady on the staircase. His
Enter Input : garret was under the roof of a high, five-storied house and was more
Enter Input : like a cupboard than a room. The landlady who provided him with garret,
Enter Input : dinners, and attendance, lived on the floor below, and every time
Enter Input : he went out he was obliged to pass her kitchen, the door of which
Enter Input : invariably stood open. And each time he passed, the young man had a
Enter Input : sick, frightened feeling, which made him scowl and feel ashamed. He was
Enter Input : hopelessly in debt to his landlady, and was afraid of meeting her.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : This was not because he was cowardly and abject, quite the contrary; but
Enter Input : for some time past he had been in an overstrained irritable condition,
Enter Input : verging on hypochondria. He had become so completely absorbed in
Enter Input : himself, and isolated from his fellows that he dreaded meeting, not
Enter Input : only his landlady, but anyone at all. He was crushed by poverty, but the
Enter Input : anxieties of his position had of late ceased to weigh upon him. He had
Enter Input : given up attending to matters of practical importance; he had lost all
Enter Input : desire to do so. Nothing that any landlady could do had a real terror
Enter Input : for him. But to be stopped on the stairs, to be forced to listen to her
Enter Input : trivial, irrelevant gossip, to pestering demands for payment, threats
Enter Input : and complaints, and to rack his brains for excuses, to prevaricate, to
Enter Input : lie--no, rather than that, he would creep down the stairs like a cat and
Enter Input : slip out unseen.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : This evening, however, on coming out into the street, he became acutely
Enter Input : aware of his fears.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : "I want to attempt a thing _like that_ and am frightened by these
Enter Input : trifles," he thought, with an odd smile. "Hm... yes, all is in a man's
Enter Input : hands and he lets it all slip from cowardice, that's an axiom. It would
Enter Input : be interesting to know what it is men are most afraid of. Taking a new
Enter Input : step, uttering a new word is what they fear most.... But I am talking
Enter Input : too much. It's because I chatter that I do nothing. Or perhaps it is
Enter Input : that I chatter because I do nothing. I've learned to chatter this
Enter Input : last month, lying for days together in my den thinking... of Jack the
Enter Input : Giant-killer. Why am I going there now? Am I capable of _that_? Is
Enter Input : _that_ serious? It is not serious at all. It's simply a fantasy to amuse
Enter Input : myself; a plaything! Yes, maybe it is a plaything."
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : The heat in the street was terrible: and the airlessness, the bustle
Enter Input : and the plaster, scaffolding, bricks, and dust all about him, and that
Enter Input : special Petersburg stench, so familiar to all who are unable to get out
Enter Input : of town in summer--all worked painfully upon the young man's already
Enter Input : overwrought nerves. The insufferable stench from the pot-houses, which
Enter Input : are particularly numerous in that part of the town, and the drunken men
Enter Input : whom he met continually, although it was a working day, completed
Enter Input : the revolting misery of the picture. An expression of the profoundest
Enter Input : disgust gleamed for a moment in the young man's refined face. He was,
Enter Input : by the way, exceptionally handsome, above the average in height, slim,
Enter Input : well-built, with beautiful dark eyes and dark brown hair. Soon he sank
Enter Input : into deep thought, or more accurately speaking into a complete blankness
Enter Input : of mind; he walked along not observing what was about him and not caring
Enter Input : to observe it. From time to time, he would mutter something, from the
Enter Input : habit of talking to himself, to which he had just confessed. At these
Enter Input : moments he would become conscious that his ideas were sometimes in a
Enter Input : tangle and that he was very weak; for two days he had scarcely tasted
Enter Input : food.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : He was so badly dressed that even a man accustomed to shabbiness would
Enter Input : have been ashamed to be seen in the street in such rags. In that quarter
Enter Input : of the town, however, scarcely any shortcoming in dress would have
Enter Input : created surprise. Owing to the proximity of the Hay Market, the number
Enter Input : of establishments of bad character, the preponderance of the trading
Enter Input : and working class population crowded in these streets and alleys in the
Enter Input : heart of Petersburg, types so various were to be seen in the streets
Enter Input : that no figure, however queer, would have caused surprise. But there was
Enter Input : such accumulated bitterness and contempt in the young man's heart, that,
Enter Input : in spite of all the fastidiousness of youth, he minded his rags least
Enter Input : of all in the street. It was a different matter when he met with
Enter Input : acquaintances or with former fellow students, whom, indeed, he disliked
Enter Input : meeting at any time. And yet when a drunken man who, for some unknown
Enter Input : reason, was being taken somewhere in a huge waggon dragged by a heavy
Enter Input : dray horse, suddenly shouted at him as he drove past: "Hey there, German
Enter Input : hatter" bawling at the top of his voice and pointing at him--the young
Enter Input : man stopped suddenly and clutched tremulously at his hat. It was a tall
Enter Input : round hat from Zimmerman's, but completely worn out, rusty with age, all
Enter Input : torn and bespattered, brimless and bent on one side in a most unseemly
Enter Input : fashion. Not shame, however, but quite another feeling akin to terror
Enter Input : had overtaken him.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : "I knew it," he muttered in confusion, "I thought so! That's the worst
Enter Input : of all! Why, a stupid thing like this, the most trivial detail might
Enter Input : spoil the whole plan. Yes, my hat is too noticeable.... It looks absurd
Enter Input : and that makes it noticeable.... With my rags I ought to wear a cap, any
Enter Input : sort of old pancake, but not this grotesque thing. Nobody wears such
Enter Input : a hat, it would be noticed a mile off, it would be remembered.... What
Enter Input : matters is that people would remember it, and that would give them
Enter Input : a clue. For this business one should be as little conspicuous as
Enter Input : possible.... Trifles, trifles are what matter! Why, it's just such
Enter Input : trifles that always ruin everything...."
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : He had not far to go; he knew indeed how many steps it was from the gate
Enter Input : of his lodging house: exactly seven hundred and thirty. He had counted
Enter Input : them once when he had been lost in dreams. At the time he had put no
Enter Input : faith in those dreams and was only tantalising himself by their hideous
Enter Input : but daring recklessness. Now, a month later, he had begun to look upon
Enter Input : them differently, and, in spite of the monologues in which he jeered at
Enter Input : his own impotence and indecision, he had involuntarily come to regard
Enter Input : this "hideous" dream as an exploit to be attempted, although he
Enter Input : still did not realise this himself. He was positively going now for a
Enter Input : "rehearsal" of his project, and at every step his excitement grew more
Enter Input : and more violent.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : With a sinking heart and a nervous tremor, he went up to a huge house
Enter Input : which on one side looked on to the canal, and on the other into the
Enter Input : street. This house was let out in tiny tenements and was inhabited by
Enter Input : working people of all kinds--tailors, locksmiths, cooks, Germans of
Enter Input : sorts, girls picking up a living as best they could, petty clerks, etc.
Enter Input : There was a continual coming and going through the two gates and in the
Enter Input : two courtyards of the house. Three or four door-keepers were employed on
Enter Input : the building. The young man was very glad to meet none of them, and
Enter Input : at once slipped unnoticed through the door on the right, and up the
Enter Input : staircase. It was a back staircase, dark and narrow, but he was familiar
Enter Input : with it already, and knew his way, and he liked all these surroundings:
Enter Input : in such darkness even the most inquisitive eyes were not to be dreaded.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : "If I am so scared now, what would it be if it somehow came to pass that
Enter Input : I were really going to do it?" he could not help asking himself as he
Enter Input : reached the fourth storey. There his progress was barred by some porters
Enter Input : who were engaged in moving furniture out of a flat. He knew that the
Enter Input : flat had been occupied by a German clerk in the civil service, and his
Enter Input : family. This German was moving out then, and so the fourth floor on this
Enter Input : staircase would be untenanted except by the old woman. "That's a good
Enter Input : thing anyway," he thought to himself, as he rang the bell of the old
Enter Input : woman's flat. The bell gave a faint tinkle as though it were made of
Enter Input : tin and not of copper. The little flats in such houses always have bells
Enter Input : that ring like that. He had forgotten the note of that bell, and now
Enter Input : its peculiar tinkle seemed to remind him of something and to bring it
Enter Input : clearly before him.... He started, his nerves were terribly overstrained
Enter Input : by now. In a little while, the door was opened a tiny crack: the old
Enter Input : woman eyed her visitor with evident distrust through the crack, and
Enter Input : nothing could be seen but her little eyes, glittering in the darkness.
Enter Input : But, seeing a number of people on the landing, she grew bolder, and
Enter Input : opened the door wide. The young man stepped into the dark entry, which
Enter Input : was partitioned off from the tiny kitchen. The old woman stood facing
Enter Input : him in silence and looking inquiringly at him. She was a diminutive,
Enter Input : withered up old woman of sixty, with sharp malignant eyes and a sharp
Enter Input : little nose. Her colourless, somewhat grizzled hair was thickly smeared
Enter Input : with oil, and she wore no kerchief over it. Round her thin long neck,
Enter Input : which looked like a hen's leg, was knotted some sort of flannel rag,
Enter Input : and, in spite of the heat, there hung flapping on her shoulders, a mangy
Enter Input : fur cape, yellow with age. The old woman coughed and groaned at every
Enter Input : instant. The young man must have looked at her with a rather peculiar
Enter Input : expression, for a gleam of mistrust came into her eyes again.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : "Raskolnikov, a student, I came here a month ago," the young man made
Enter Input : haste to mutter, with a half bow, remembering that he ought to be more
Enter Input : polite.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : "I remember, my good sir, I remember quite well your coming here," the
Enter Input : old woman said distinctly, still keeping her inquiring eyes on his face.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : "And here... I am again on the same errand," Raskolnikov continued, a
Enter Input : little disconcerted and surprised at the old woman's mistrust. "Perhaps
Enter Input : she is always like that though, only I did not notice it the other
Enter Input : time," he thought with an uneasy feeling.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : The old woman paused, as though hesitating; then stepped on one side,
Enter Input : and pointing to the door of the room, she said, letting her visitor pass
Enter Input : in front of her:
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : "Step in, my good sir."
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : The little room into which the young man walked, with yellow paper on
Enter Input : the walls, geraniums and muslin curtains in the windows, was brightly
Enter Input : lighted up at that moment by the setting sun.
Enter Input : 
