Enter Input : chance through Raskolnikov's mind, and with a rapid glance he scanned
Enter Input : everything in the room, trying as far as possible to notice and
Enter Input : remember its arrangement. But there was nothing special in the room. The
Enter Input : furniture, all very old and of yellow wood, consisted of a sofa with
Enter Input : a huge bent wooden back, an oval table in front of the sofa, a
Enter Input : dressing-table with a looking-glass fixed on it between the windows,
Enter Input : chairs along the walls and two or three half-penny prints in yellow
Enter Input : frames, representing German damsels with birds in their hands--that was
Enter Input : all. In the corner a light was burning before a small ikon. Everything
Enter Input : was very clean; the floor and the furniture were brightly polished;
Enter Input : everything shone.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : "Lizaveta's work," thought the young man. There was not a speck of dust
Enter Input : to be seen in the whole flat.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : "It's in the houses of spiteful old widows that one finds such
Enter Input : cleanliness," Raskolnikov thought again, and he stole a curious glance
Enter Input : at the cotton curtain over the door leading into another tiny room, in
Enter Input : which stood the old woman's bed and chest of drawers and into which he
Enter Input : had never looked before. These two rooms made up the whole flat.
Enter Input : 
Enter Input : "What do you want?" the old woman said severely, coming into the room
Enter Input : and, as before, standing in front of him so as to look him straight in
Enter Input : the face.
Enter Input : 
